<font color="#FF0000">VARIOUS REPLIES</font><br>
<tt>Mon Mar 10  1:46:22 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
First to Doc Del, <br>
Sorry to be such a densoid.  I actually thought you meant that you wanted to mix it up in debate with some of the other people on the site.  Had no intention of using you as a back channel to Jeffrey; though I realize after reading your post, that talking to you in a public forum would probably have that affect.  I was pressed for time, and I probably didn't think things through enough.  Didn't mean to give offense.  Have not tried to go over anyone's head either.  Usually can take a lot of shit, but find it very hard to take when someone tells me two of the most honest and perceptive people I know, my parents, either lied about what happened at a time I was only 3, or didn't know what was actually happening.  No need for anybody else to pick up the cudgels.  This is my problem.  <br><br>
To Tom Dier, <br>
You managed to pick some of Jeffrey's statements I have no problem with.  I am well aware that Britain purposely had war materiel shipped on liners in the hope that the Germans would sink something, kill some civilians and enrage the American public; so we would enter WWI.  Also am aware that the southern boundary of Texas was disputed by Mexico in 1845.  Mexico claimed all the land south of the Nueces River.  Zachary Taylor's troops were sent over the Nueces in what was a successful attempt to provoke a Mexican attack.  In Congress, Abraham Lincoln stated: &quot;I don't believe there was ever a more wicked war waged by any nation.&quot;  A bit of hyperbole perhaps, but we definately had dirty hands.  As for Clinton's conduct of foreign policy; I have grave doubts as to his ability to distinguish his short term self interest from the long term interests of his country.  That said, I'm of the same mind as Churchill: &quot;Democracy is the worst form of government except for all the others.&quot;  It's not that democracies are not up to crises, but have trouble staying the course when nothing major absolutely requires a concerted effort.  It's part of the price we pay for polictical freedom.  <br><br>
To Doc Spatz, <br>
One of things I came home with from Vietnam, was an acute appreciation for the absurd and gallows humor.  I admit that I cannot speak for my brothers who pounded up and down the boondocks.  I can only count on one hand the number of times I was really in serious danger to my knowledge.  However, life on an LZ continuously had dozens of quirks that had elements of humor.  Being able to laugh at the incongruities helped get a guy through the year.  Some examples: <br>
     1. One of the items in highest demand was plastic      toilet seats.  Wooden seats rotted in the heat and      produced splinters.  We had a 23 year warrant officer      who was a match for Sgt Bilko.  You name it, he could<br>
     get it.  He had taken a lieutenant back at our rear<br>
     area in An Khe under his wing.  One day the major said: <br>
     &quot;Wouldn't it be nice if we had some plastic toilet      seats.&quot;  About four days later it seems someone made a <br>
     midnight requisition on the Engineers' compound.  Ten<br>
     days later, the Red Cross women dropped by LZ English <br>
     for the major's birthday with 3 large gift wrapped      packages.  <br>
     2. Definition - Seriously Dead: A condition extremely      more grave than Seriously Wounded, but considerably      less painful. <br>
     3. There was considerable debate whether HQ mess was  <br>
     capable of making a mediocre cup of coffee, good being<br>
     very unlikely and excellent being unattainable.<br>
                             Gerry
